@node "why" "Introduction"
 
 The "why writing a DeliPlay module" is very simple: This should be
 a test to write a DOpus module with Maxon-C 3.0. And this also if
 only SAS-C is supported by the developer packet of DOpus.
 A internal command of DOpus is also @{fg shine}better@{fg text} (and faster) than an
 ARexx script and can do more options.
 
 The german guide and the "pre" of the english guide was written with 
 "AMIS 1.0" by Willem Mestrom and over the registration limit of AMIS
 editet with "GoldEd" 4.4 by Dietmar Eilert.
 Helpful was for development "HotHelp 3" by Maxon and 
 "fd2pragma" 2.2 by Dirk Stoecker.
 Also used "CatComp" (Commodore) and "CatEdit" 1.2 by Rafael D'Halleweyn.
 Developed on an A 4000 EC 030, 68882 FPU, 2/8 MB. 
 
 @{" Requirements " LINK "required"}

@endnode
@node "required" "Requirements"
 
 Software:  DOpus Version 5.5 or higher,
            DeliTracker 2.X or higher
 
 Hardware:  Kick/WB 2.1 or higher,
            Processor 68020 or higher,
            enough Memory to run all programs 
            (2/2 MB think I is minimum, 
             2/4 MB = no problems,
             more -> you have more than enough, 
                     send a part of it to me ;-)
 
 @{" Installation " LINK "install"}

@endnode
@node "install" "Installation"
 
 There will be two requests first :
 
 1. a file request:
    "Where is the DeliTracker ?"
 
    Click the path @{fg shine}and@{fg text} the file "DeliTracker2".
 
 2. A query with "Yes" and "No" button:
    "Install filetypes for modules ?"
 
    They are not needed, if you do not what to use "DeliPlay" with
    a doubleclick on a file. But it is useful, to forward simple
    modules (like ProTracker) to the @{fg shine}MultiPlayer@{fg text} or other.
    He is for these modules faster loaded. But for other modules
    (like S3M) you must use a special player and that is why you
    must make a difference between modules and their filetypes.
    This is @{fg shine}not the answer@{fg text} for all problems, this filetypes can
    only distinguish between different suffixes.
    This means that i.e. a ProTracker module must begin/end with
    mod./.mod . To make differences with a group of bytes in the
    file is not a good idea, this does not work with packed files
    (all my mods are XPK/CRMS packed). 
    The command in the filetypes you must change to what you wish
    after install, predefined is "DeliPlay HideFull".
 
 Afterwards begins the selfworking install.
 
 If you want to remove any same working ARexx script you have to do
 this yourself (and on your own risk).
 
 After a new start of DOpus you can use 
 
 @{" The new commands " LINK "new commands"} 

@endnode
@node "new commands" "The new commands"
 
 There will be only two new commands:
 
 "DeliStop" - ends the DeliTracker 
 
 and
 
 "DeliPlay" - starts the DeliTracker, if he is not already running, and
              control him with the options.
              The loading of modules will get them from @{fg shine}all@{fg text} source
              listers (DOpus 5.5 has a small bug here, but may be later ...)
 
 @{" The start options " LINK "startoptions"}

@endnode
@node "startoptions" "The start options"
 
 The command "DeliPlay" has several options, but only @{fg shine}one@{fg text} will be
 used. 
 
 @{fg shine}needs@{fg text} selected @{fg shine}files@{fg text} in a source lister:
 
 ShowGui           - starts the DeliTracker visible
 
 ShowAppIcon       - starts the DeliTracker as appicon
 
 HideFull           - starts the DeliTracker hidden
 
 (no option)       - starts the DeliTracker in the saved mode
                     (in DOpus5:settings/DT.cfg)
 
 @{" The control options " LINK "control"}   

@endnode
@node "control" "The control options"
 
 @{fg shine}no@{fg text} selected @{fg shine}files@{fg text} in any source lister @{fg shine}allowed@{fg text}:
 
 ShowGui           - make the DeliTracker visible
 
 ShowAppIcon       - switch the DeliTracker to an appicon
 
 HideFull          - hide the DeliTracker full
 
 (no options)      - nothing

 
 selected @{fg shine}files@{fg text} in a source lister @{fg shine}allowed, but ignored@{fg text}:
 
 Loop              - play the current module endless
 
 Next              - ends the "Loop" state, plays the next module
 
 Prev              - ends the "Loop" state, plays the previous module
 
 Pause             - stay at current position in module, or
                     go on playing
 
 @{" Loading options " LINK "loading"}

@endnode
@node "loading" "Loading options"
 
 Here you can use the same options like @{"The start options" LINK "startoptions"} of the 
 DeliTracker. But the @{fg shine}option@{fg text} will be @{fg shine}ignored@{fg text}.
 
 This means, if you have started the DeliTracker hidden,
 you can use a button with the command "DeliPlay ShowGui" to load
 new modules, @{fg shine}without@{fg text} the DeliTracker will become visible.
 
 Of course you can use drag and drop to the appicon or window
 of the DeliTracker.
 
 @{" Usage in filetypes " LINK "filetypes"} 

@endnode
@node "filetypes" "Usage in filetypes"
 
 You can here use any option from @{" The start options " LINK "startoptions"}. The option
 will be ignored if the DeliTracker is already running.
 
 The command line can look like this (as command):
 
 DeliPlay HideFull
 
 @{" Problems " LINK "problems"} 

@endnode
@node "problems" "Problems"
 
 It is not by me but if you want to change the state of visible, the
 DeliTracker @{fg shine}must be made visible@{fg text} for a short time. Because if you 
 want to change from appicon to full hidden and this were not build
 in, the appicon does not remove.
 
 The DeliTracker will @{fg shine}not start@{fg text} (of course) if the audio channels are
 @{fg shine}already allocated@{fg text}.  
 
 The time the lister is blocked if the DeliTracker starts new, is
 set by the DeliTracker, because he does not mount his port until
 then.
 
 It would be useful, if you start most times the DeliTracker in 
 hidden mode to add to the exit script of DOpus "DeliStop" or use
 later Exchange to quit/show the DeliTracker.
 
 @{" The author " LINK "author"}

@endnode
